Japan, India, Singapore, China: Asian Local Bonds and Currency Previews

-- B y   Y u m i   T e s o
-- 
2011-03-16T22:11:25Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-16/japan-india-singapore-china-asian-local-bonds-and-currency-previews.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.    Japan : The yen reached a post-World War II high of 76.36
per dollar as the risk of radiation leaks from crippled nuclear
plants in Japan added to speculation insurers and investors will
redeem overseas assets to pay for damages. The currency was at
77.60 as of 6:55 a.m. in Tokyo.  Yukiya Amano, head of the  International Atomic Energy
Agency , is flying to Tokyo to talk with authorities today before
an emergency meeting planned by the United Nations’ nuclear
agency in Vienna.  The Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry will report
Japan’s tertiary industry activity at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo.  The Ministry of Finance will release a report on weekly
securities transactions at 8:50 a.m.  Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold regular media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due March 2021
was 1.22 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.    China : China Development Bank will sell 20 billion yuan ($3
billion) each of seven-year bonds and seven-year floaters.  The yield on the government’s 3.77 percent bond due
December 2020 was 3.9 percent. The yuan was at 6.5714.    India : The  Reserve Bank  of India will boost the repurchase
rate by a quarter percentage point to 6.75 percent, according to
all 26 economists surveyed by Bloomberg before a policy review
today.  Food inflation data for the week ended March 5 is due
today. An index measuring wholesale prices of agricultural
products, rice and vegetables rose 9.52 percent in the week
through Feb. 26 from a year earlier.  The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.96
percent. The rupee was at 45.1175.  Singapore: Non-oil domestic exports increased 10.5 percent
in February from a year earlier after rising 20.9 percent the
previous month, according to the median forecast in a Bloomberg
survey.  The yield on the 3.25 percent debt due September 2020 was
2.30 percent. The  Singapore  dollar was at S$1.2844.  To contact the reporter on this story:
